        <section id="prologue">
            <h2>Prologue</h2>

            <p><i>"No matter what happens, you mustn't let go of my hand."</i></p>

            <p>You woke up in a rocking chair, a fireplace on your right, and a pale maid looking at you with a gentle smile.</p>

            <p>You probably have heard these first few words, or variations of them, on many works before, so you might scoff at such a beginning. But this is how Fata begins, with me as a reader, and The Maid, waiting for me to wake up.</p>
                
            <p>At the outset, I was immediately captured by the atmosphere of the art. It’s not at all detailed, on the contrary, it is very messy, like a painting made by a 10th-century artist who has never experienced the Renaissance yet, but it drives in the point of how dilapidated the setting the story took place. The Mansion itself, abandoned, has found its new master, and that master was me.</p>
                
            <p>Maybe not me, but this unknown male character, that the maid has been waiting for, for a long time. Without our memory intact, the Maid then invites us to explore the Mansion, to piece together our memories so that we can properly become the master of the Mansion. She gave us a tour of the mansion itself, passing through the stained-glass window and mirrors, and arrived near the garden.</p>
                
            <p>This short beginning was enough to fully immerse me within the story itself and got me caught up in the mystery of who is our protagonist, and what kind of story we will experience to get him to remember himself.</p>
                
            <p>The smell of roses fills the air as we open the first door.</p>
        </section>
        <section id="first-door">
            <h2>The First Door</h2>
            <h3>2012</h3>

            <p><i>"Mell, you'll always be my prince, right?"</i></p>
            <p><i>"Al, you'll always be there for me, right?"</i></p>

            <p>The Shakespearean influence on this door is strong, and not just because it smells like roses. Coming from a series where the story involves heavily with siblings, this door feels almost familiar and warmth, yet just like how rose would smell sweet but prick your fingers as you pick it, this story is not what it seems.</p>

            <p>Shakespeare <i>loves</i> tragedy, and he would have <i>loved</i> this story. Behind the door lies the first master of the mansion, taking the name of Rose Manor at this time, Mell Rhodes. A noble who lives with his sister, Nellie Rhodes, their siblings relationship was the highlight of this door. I personally cannot actually relate to Mell as I'm the youngest sibling, but being treated like a prince by his younger sister...</p>

            <p>Their lives were relatively peaceful before the appearance of one peculiar white-haired girl, the same white-haired girl I saw in the main menu of this game. I remember thinking that perhaps we are that girl, when I first read this door, very late into it.</p>

            <p>I could never have guessed that the development of this story would head towards, however.</p>

            <p>Nellie's love towards his brother... was much more intense than I had expected. When she was handling that sharp object and head towards the white-haired girl, in jealousy after she and Mell grew close together, I didn't expect her to cut off her hair, and <i>wear</i> it.</p>

            <p>I expected her to scalp her clean, and wear her scalp. The horror aspect of this story... I was warned before I read this that the story would be heavy, but I still wasn't ready to face how scary it can be.</p>

            <p>Once the story reached its end, Mell kneeling in the rain, losing pretty much everything that he holds dear, the door ends, and we returned to the mansion. The protagonist's memories still not returning.</p>

            <p>Other than the story itself, once again I need to highlight how the soundtrack help me get immersed with the setting and the story itself, happy tune of <i>Petalouda</i> or <i>Cetoniinae</i>, the depressing <i>Acherontia Styx</i>, or the panic-inducing <i>Tarantula</i> or <i>Labirintia</i>, the soundtrack just from the <i>first</i> door has brought me more emotions than what I expected from the medium.</p>

            <p>As for the story itself, the innocent dynamic turned into dark portrayal of how sibling relationship can be, it's stellar. It gives me dread, but this is only a pittance compared to the dread that the other doors would instill in me.</p>

            <p>And so the mansion opens its second door, behind which we can hear the sound of a... dangerous beast.</p>
        </section>
        <section id="second-door">
            <h2>The Second Door</h2>
            <h3>2009</h3>

            <p><i>"I am not xxxxxxxx.... I am the Beast!"</i></p>
            <p><i>"Al, stop!"</i></p>

            <p>Before I began delving into my thoughts of the Second Door, there were intermission in between the door that I'd like to talk about. A mirror that reveals a scene where a man in long white hair reveals himself as a witch. An important scene that I only get the meaning of in later doors. I love how they already planted seeds of that story very early on, and looking back at it, the story reveals enough for me to speculate, but not enough context to know the whole truth. This kind of technique in story-telling is something I admire, and wish I can do for my own series in the future, but I digress. The door awaits me.</p>

            <p>Behind this door reeks smell of rust, of blood spilled and of a ravenous beast. This is my LEAST favorite door, even though in this series that means nothing. The other door simply was too good in comparison.</p>

            <p>And the story being told here touches on things that I don't particularly like.</p>

            <p>It sets the story hundreds of years after the era of the Rose Manor, of Mell and Nellie and the White-Haired Girl. The mansion is now dilapidated, abandoned. No master has appeared, until one day, a beast makes its way to the mansion, taking the name Weeping Manor.</p>

            <p>The mansion's second Master.</p>

            <p>From the start, I can already sense the similarity, or rather, inspiration, towards the story <i>Beauty and the Beast</i>. I was eagerly waiting for the "Beauty" to come and brought the beast back to humanity. The Maid did help him start learning how to converse with human language at first, whilst before, he just screeched unintelligibly. It was enough to make me uncomfortable, and the narration by the maid who also felt uncomfortable by the sight of the beast didn't help.</p>

            <p>My naivete only lasts for so long. The beast is indeed a beast, even when he can speak, as he used that skill to pass as a human to weary traveler finding their way to the mansion... and proceeded to kill them and eat them.</p>

            <p>I don't need to elaborate on what I thought about that.</p>

            <p>The story then sometimes would jump to a girl, Pauline, waiting for her beau, a merchant who travels the sea. She received news that he was dead, but she refuses to believe in such news, and looked everywhere for him, finally able to find information of his last whereabout, in a village... near the mansion.</p>

            <p>The third party in this story is a blind white-haired girl, one of the people who was lured in by the mystical force of the Mansion and the boundless sphere of Fate. The "Beauty" in this story, the one I've been waiting for.</p>

            <p>Their story intertwines with each other, but the writers managed to mislead me long enough that I was floored when the reveal happened.</p>

            <p>I didn't expect the beast to be an exploration of racism, out of all things. The Merchant, who was revealed to be of Eastern (possibly Japanese) descent, <i>is</i> the Beast. He was called the Beast by people of the nearby village, after his appearance, and later on, because he killed people.</p>

            <p>For the door's duration, we never see his appearance, the beast was shrouded in shadow, as it was how the beast views himself, a clever way to both mislead the reader and somehow accurately portrays how a broken man can view himself.</p>

            <p>I won't talk about the twist nor the ending here, I still don't like to think about it. This door, however, proves to me that this game was indeed going to be really dark moving forward, and the depiction of the beasts, how he kills people, some of the CG, was definitely leaning towards horror, which I hated with all of my being.</p>

            <p>This level of horror usually would make me stop reading a series. But I did read this particular door with my Buddy Grace, so the impact was lessened a bit knowing someone was there watching with me.</p>

            <p>And even after all that, this door does have some lighthearted moment in it, between Pauline and the local boy Javi, but their antics was nowhere near close for me to wipe out the rest of the... atrocities committed on this door.</p>

            <p>And so the mansion opens its third door, to a sound of pool balls, and smell of tobacco.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="third-door">
            <h2>The Third Door</h2>
            <h3>2013</h3>

            <p><i>"Don't talk to other men!"</i></p>
            <p><i>"Don't talk back to me! Just listen to me, Al! You have a problem-"</i></p>

            <p>This door...</p>

            <p>This door elicits more anger from me in the early doors. The last time I was this angry about something, I was really close to dropping the series.</p>

            <p>The mansion behind this door has been rehabilitated by the third Master, Jacopo.</p>

            <p>Even though the last door was bad, there are still parts of them that I can talk about. Not this door. Out of anger that would be understandable once you read through this portion if you played the game, I will make this one VERY short.</p>

            <p>Jacopo is the master, and White-Haired Girl is here as his wife. They met through an arranged marriage. The other girl in this door are Maria, an old friend of Jacopo who now worked as his maid.</p>

            <p>What works in this door? It successfully evoke the late 1800s atmosphere to me immediately, with its soundtrack <i>Ciao Carina</i> evoking the most of that feeling.</p>

            <p>It successfully portrays manipulative and abusive characters, so much so that I'd rather not name them, or talk about them, due to how frustrated I would sound like.</p>

            <p>It also takes the early cake for being the most depressing story. But as I learned of the later door, this would take its rightful place of being third, behind the other, more tragic characters  and stories.</p>

            <p>Portion of this door's story also somehow reminds me of a telenovela, which might be inspired by it? I'm not sure myself, but I can see these kinds of story playing out in a telenovela somewhere. I swear I saw one scene of a telenovela where a lot of people pointed a gun at each other and it was shown in this drawn up dramatic way. Not at all what happens here, but the story here reminds me of that.</p>

            <p>There's nothing else I'd like to talk about this door, not in this kind of capacity anyway. I still rank this door objectively above the first and second, only because it evokes more emotions in me than that two doors.</p>

            <p>And so the mansion opens its last door, where I can see endless stair rising above, the observation tower that held the secret to all.</p>

        </section>

