        <section id="fifth-door">
            <h2>The Fifth Door</h2>
            <h3>2010-2017</h3>

            <p><i>"I feel unclean..."</i></p>
            <p><i>"...powerless as I sat there for hours."</i></p>

            <p>Welcome to the real story.</p>

            <p>The mansion only has four doors, and this door is more like the same door but not altered by illusions and fantasies.</p>

            <p>As the main character... <i>reclaim himself</i>, we came to learn that the story was twisted, and the White-Haired Girl who introduces herself as Giselle was a fabrication, and instead, <i>The Maid</i> was Giselle.</p>

            <p>And we, the main character, are Michel, the hermit who lived in the mansion and died protecting Giselle, just like the previous door.</p>

            <p>In this door, we are treated to a longer, more intricate story about how Michel and Giselle meet with each other. We learned more about Giselle, who was a maid to the Bollinger family, Michel's family.</p>

            <p>This door was such a shock compared to the previous one for me, and at some point I have to skip portion of the story due to how uncomfortable it made me feel. But unlike the other doors, there are parts of the story here that shines brighter, balancing out the scale that leans far enough already towards depression. Even though the ending remains the same as the fourth door, this time, the story feels more complete, more realistic.</p>

            <p>It feels like it has a heart.</p>

            <p>But, as I progressed through the story again, it is only one part of the bigger picture.</p>

            <p>It is time to enter the door that hides the true heart of The Maid, or Giselle, and help her reclaim herself.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="sixth-door">
            <h2>The Sixth Door</h2>
            <h3>xxxx - xxxx</h3>

            <p><i>"Michel... where are you? I've waited and waited and waited-"</i></p>
            <p><i>"-and waited. Al... where are you?</i></p>

            <p>Love can cross through space and time. I learned about that from the Christopher Nolan movie <i>Interstellar</i>. It also can be quantified as gravity, but we don't need to delve deep into that.</p>

            <p>Giselle's determination to wait until Michel can be reconstituted was painful to look at. The disintegration of her psyche as she was stuck with Morgana's taunting voice as her only source of stimulus, was nothing short of depressing to experience. For a love she only been with for a month, known for a year, she was willing to endure that for hundreds of years.</p>

            <p>Her depth of love is nothing to scoff at, I feel small in comparison when I look at my own.</p>

            <p>The story also ties in portion of the first three doors, of how Giselle slowly start her transformation to become the Maid we all know and love from the earlier part of the story. We see how Mell's grandfather taught her all the mannerism to be a maid, but she has to watch as his son (Mell's father) poisoned him to gain his estate, the mansion.</p> 
            
            <p>We see Giselle surviving through the Beast's reign on the mansion, thankfully we don't seem to dwell on him too long. And lastly, we see The Maid, fully transformed by the time of Jacopo's occupation, and her perspective of the tragic tale that lurks behind the third door.</p>

            <p>The door didn't end there, however. I was pleasantly surprised to see that the story continues after the door to Giselle's mind ends, and we were served instead the backstory of Morgana, the Witch. The one responsible for all the tragedy that happened in the first three door.</p>

            <p>At this point, the story has told me harrowing stories that honestly feels like a hurricane blowing me off my feet, taking me with them as if I'm a leaf. This story, however, is the rainstorm that pellets me with its droplet, pushed me to the ground, and peppers me relentlessly.</p>

            <p>The human cruelty knows no bounds. I was faced with that fact as I look on, at the river of blood and pains that stretched through the limits of humanity, not knowing that I would be served something even worse soon.</p>

            <p>As we were forced to enter the door hidden beneath Michel's heart, the one door he does not want to open, the past he would rather keep tight in his heart for himself.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="seventh-door">
            <h2>The Seventh Door</h2>
            <h3>2021</h3>
            
            <p><i>"We're brothers, right?"</i></p>
            <p><i>"Family is forever, right, mom?"</i></p>

            <p>This door... hits me harder than anything else. Not in a way that left me sobbing like a mess, even though it does do that as well, but because of... similarities to my own life. Only part of it, however.</p>

            <p>This door, along with the Second Door, and the Sixth Door (Morgana's part), is part of the reason why even though this is peak storytelling, I cannot really ever recommend this to read for others.</p>

            <p>For a lack of a better term, the Trauma... Conga Line (thanks TVTropes) lining up in this door was layered perfectly, like a wedding cake made out of hatred and contains blood of the innocents.</p>

            <p>We can go through the checklist if you want. Transgender Tragedy? Check. Parental Abuse? Check. Familial Abuse? Checkity check check. Abandonment issues? Check. Betrayal of the highest order, by your own brothers? Check.</p>

            <p>You know the part that got me the most after this? There is no closure. No satisfying comeback. What we get is an abuser, who managed to live like royalty after abusing the living fuck out of an innocent child. What we get is a mother, burning their rotting corpse on a stake, calling them a demon child, while said child was looking on in a spirit form.</p>

            <p>I have to sit there for a moment and <i>really</i> take that in. This is reality. This is how it is in real life. It's not a fictional story, these kind of things happen to people in real life, but maybe they don't have to watch as the person who brings them to life burn their fucking corpse and call them horrible fucking names-</p>

            <p>..............</p>

            <p>I took a day off, even though at that point, the deadline was a few days left for the reviews.</p>

            <p>I needed to take my mind off the story, to make sure I was able to focus and finish the story with a healthy mindset. This is what they warned me about when they say that this story is heavy.</p>

            <p>I know this coming in. Even through all that horrifying things, I still recognize this as a story. It gives me peace. It distanced me from the depressing stuff. It's all fictional. I am not Michel, and honestly, I can never <i>be</i> Michel. After all that harrowing experience, you know what he did when he was offered to curse the people who hurt him? He <i>refuses</i>.</p>

            <p>Michel always wanted to be a Knight. He never got to be a knight, but in my heart, he's the epitome of what a Knight should be. This guy... I can't help but admire him.</p>

            <p>But also this guy... is too perfect to ever exist in real life. If I ever meet someone as perfect as him in real life... I would be surprised.</p>

            <p>Either way, the ending to this door alleviated some of the heavy stuff that permeated throughout, and with that feeling in mind, we stepped in to the final Door, the door into Morgana's heart, to find out the perspective of those who keep her caged in the observation tower, to find the truth, and to end the cycle of hate.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="final-door">
            <h2>The Final Door</h2>
            <h3>xxxx - xxxx</h3>
            
            <p><i>"Fantasies are not everlasting. They all crumble eventually."</i></p>
            <p><i>"People are supposed to be able to feel happy or sad for each other... I can't though, which must make me a beast."</i></p>
            <p><i>"Events by themselves do not tell the whole story. Only when you take into account their circumstances, what they thought and felt, their perspectives—only then you can say you've reached the truth."</i></p>
            <p><i>"You were the only one to ever have pity for me... and I shall be the only one to have compassion for you. You were the only one to stay at my side... and I shall do the same for you."</i></p>

            <p>This door is honestly a fever dream from the start.</p>

            <p>First of all, everyone is here, like Smash Ultimate bringing back all the characters throughout their series. The story behind Morgana's door reveals that all of the characters we've seen so far was involved in Morgana's final fate. The three men whose tragic fates drives the first three doors were the one responsible for Morgana's suffering. They bear three keys, almost the same like their shadows during a portion of the story in the Sixth Door, or its intermission, you can say.</p>

            <p>And then we have both Michel and Giselle, finally reunited, but Giselle is instead a disembodied voice residing inside Michel, that can see through his eyes and talk to him telepathically. Their dynamic was one of the highlights of the door, for me. But there's also another thing that shines just as bright.</p>

            <p>Perhaps it was because of the length of time it took between the First Door and the Final Door for me, but when we meet Nellie once more... her ending up being probably the best part of this door was downright ludicrous thought, I would never be able to guess. This same, still a bit pompous but more little-sister-like character captured my heart immediately at the first sight of her antics.</p>

            <p>The theme for this door is about finding out truth from all three men, and their keys, so that we can see their perspectives and to provide closure to Morgana, so that she can reverse the darkness enveloping the mansion, and let go of her past.</p>

            <p>The ending for this door left me sobbing, crying, cursing softly. It twisted my heart into hoping that it'll be alright, then I was reminded that this story is all illusions still. The past can't be changed. What's happened, happened.</p>

